SIMPLE: waist
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Waist
<hw>Waist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wast</ets>;
originally, growth, akin to AS. <ets>weaxan</ets> to grow; cf. AS.
<ets>w⟦ae⟧stm</ets> growth. See <er>Wax</er> to grow.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>That part of the human body which is immediately
below the ribs or thorax; the small part of the body between the thorax
and hips.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am in the <qex>waist</qex> two yards about.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, the middle part of other bodies; especially
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, that part of a vessel's deck, bulwarks, etc., which
is between the quarter-deck and the forecastle; the middle part of the
ship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A garment, or part of a garment, which covers the
body from the neck or shoulders to the waist line.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A girdle or belt for the waist.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Waist anchor</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Sheet anchor</er>, 1,
in the Vocabulary.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Waistband</ent>⟦br⟧
